Fighting Disease
Defences Against Disease
That the body has physical barriers to disease, which include the skin, mucus in the nose and
airways, and cilia which line the trachea and bronchi.
That the body has chemical barriers to disease, which include hydrochloric acid produced in the
stomach and lysozymes.
That if pathogens do manage to enter the body, the immune system can attack them — some white
blood cells non-specically engulf pathogens by phagocytosis, and other white blood cells called
B-lymphocytes produce antibodies in response to antigens in the specic immune response.
That antibodies bind to antigens on pathogens so that the pathogens can be found and destroyed by
other white blood cells.
Memory Lymphocytes and Immunisation
That when a foreign antigen on the surface of a pathogen enters the body for the rst time, it triggers
the production of specialised white blood cells called memory lymphocytes.
That memory lymphocytes remain in the body for a long period of time and can ‘remember’ the
antigen that triggered their production in the primary immune response to that antigen.
That the secondary immune response is faster and stronger than the primary immune response, as
memory lymphocytes recognise the antigens on the pathogen and mass produce antibodies specic
to that antigen.
That immunisation usually involves injecting dead or inactive pathogens to trigger the production of
antibodies and memory lymphocytes. If a live version of the same pathogen then enters the body,
memory lymphocytes can rapidly mass-produce the right antibodies to kill it so that the person is
less likely to get ill.
Pros and Cons of Immunisation
That immunisation programmes have helped to reduce and in some cases, eliminate, the occurrence
of certain diseases in the UK, and that if enough people are immune to a certain pathogen, it can
reduce the spread of the pathogen. This is known as herd immunity.
That vaccinations don’t always provide immunity, and that some people can have a bad reaction to a
vaccine.
That the risks of vaccination should be balanced up against the risk of catching the disease that the
vaccine is designed to protect against.
Monoclonal Antibodies
H
That monoclonal antibodies are produced from lots of clones of a single B-lymphocyte, and that
they will only bind to one specic protein antigen, so can target a particular cell or chemical.
H
How monoclonal antibodies are made — a lymphocyte (that doesn’t divide easily) and myeloma
cell (that divides lots) are fused to create a hybridoma, which is cloned to produce lots of identical
cells which all produce the same antibodies.
